 areas of American law. She focuses on judicial decisions-both the outcomes and the rationales-and what they say about family, rights, sexual orientation, and who qualifies as a parent. Richman challenges prevailing notions that gay and lesbian parents and families are hurt by laws’ indeterminacy, arguing that, because family law is so loosely defined, it allows for the flexibility needed to respond to-and even facilitate - changes in how we conceive of family, parenting, and the role of sexual orientation in family law.Drawing on every recorded judicial decision in gay and lesbian adoption and custody cases over the last fifty years, and on interviews with parents, lawyers, and judges, Richman demonstrates how parental and sexual identities are formed and interpreted in law, and how gay and lesbian parents can harness indeterminacy to transform family law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGay parentsxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aGay parentsxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aGay parentsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aLAW / Family Law / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aKimberly.  aRichman.  aareas.  adiscretionary.  afamily.  aindeterminate.  alaw.  amost.  anebulous.  arealm.  azeros.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081477595040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814777442.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814777442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814777442/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPAL